  1. Model development for regression linear regression random forests gradient boosting machines,
library(randomForest)
library(rpart)
library(ISLR)
library(dplyr)
library(xgboost)

n <- 10
B <- 20

lm_rmse <- c()
RF_RMSPE <-c()
RMSPE_B <-c()

for (i in 1:n) {
ind <- sample(nrow(df1), nrow(df1), replace = TRUE)
train <- df1[ind, ]
test <- df1[-ind, ]

yhat <- matrix(0, nrow(test), B)

#Random Forest  
rf_model <- randomForest(shares ~., ntree = B, data = train) 
yhat1 <- predict(rf_model, test)
RF_RMSPE[i] <- sqrt(mean((test$shares - yhat1)^2))

# localImp = TRUE
## comparing with parametric model
lm_model <- lm(shares ~ ., data=train) ##what about glm
lm_pred <- predict(lm_model, test)
lm_rmse[i] <- sqrt(mean((lm_pred - test$shares)^2))


#BAGGING
  for (j in 1:B) {
    indBB <- sample(nrow(train), nrow(train), replace = TRUE)
    trBB <- train[indBB, ]
    
    model <- rpart(shares ~ ., data = trBB, method = "anova")
    yhat[ ,j] <- predict(model, test)
  }
  yhatB <- apply(yhat, 1, mean) 
  RMSPE_B[i] <- sqrt(mean((test$shares - yhatB)^2))
}

  1. Model development for classification
library(randomForest)
library(PASWR)
library(ROCR)
library(rpart)

average <- mean(df1$shares)

nwshares <-ifelse(df1$shares < average, "unpopular", "popular")
newdata <- cbind(df1, nwshares)
newdata <- newdata[, -59]


newdata$nwshares <- as.factor(newdata$nwshares)



df <- newdata #for rpart
dff <- df[complete.cases(df),] # for rf

n <- 10
B <- 20
AUC1 <- c()
AUC2 <- c()
AUC3 <- c()

for (i in 1:n) {
  ind <- sample(nrow(df), nrow(df), replace = TRUE)
  train <- df[ind, ]
  test <- df[-ind, ]
  
  ind <- sample(nrow(dff), nrow(dff), replace = TRUE)
  train2 <- dff[ind, ]
  test2 <- dff[-ind, ]
  
  p = ncol(train2)-1

  model1 <- rpart(nwshares~.,
                data=train2, method="class") #cart
  model2 <- randomForest(nwshares~.,
                         ntree = B, mtry = p, data = train2) #Bagged
  model3 <- randomForest(nwshares~.,
                         ntree = B, data = train2) # RF    
  
  phat1 <- predict(model1, test2, type = "prob")
  phat2 <- predict(model2, test2, type = "prob")
  phat3 <- predict(model3, test2, type = "prob")
  
  #AUC1
  pred_rocr1 <- prediction(phat1[,2], test2$nwshares)
  auc_ROCR1 <- performance(pred_rocr1, measure = "auc")
  AUC1[i] <- auc_ROCR1@y.values[[1]]
  
  #AUC2
  pred_rocr2 <- prediction(phat2[,2], test2$nwshares)
  auc_ROCR2 <- performance(pred_rocr2, measure = "auc")
  AUC2[i] <- auc_ROCR2@y.values[[1]]
  
  #AUC3
  pred_rocr3 <- prediction(phat3[,2], test2$nwshares)
  auc_ROCR3 <- performance(pred_rocr3, measure = "auc")
  AUC3[i] <- auc_ROCR3@y.values[[1]]
}

                    train$Y, tree_depth = 1,
                    n_rounds = 50)

    pred_rocR <- prediction(phat, val$Y)
    auc_ROCR <- performance(pred_rocR, measure = "auc")
    aucc[i] <- auc_ROCR@y.values[[1]]
  }
  MAUC[r] <- mean(aucc)
}

# This function take `ct` and make a better table
gct <- function(x) {
  conf_table <- matrix(0, 2, 2)
  conf_table[1, 1] <- ifelse(sum(dim(x)) > 3, x[2, 2], 0)
  conf_table[2, 2] <- ifelse(sum(dim(x)) > 3, x[1, 1], 0)
  conf_table[1, 2] <- ifelse(sum(dim(x)) > 3, x[2, 1], 0)
  conf_table[2, 1] <- ifelse(sum(dim(x)) > 3, x[1, 2], 0)
  colnames(conf_table) <- c("Y=1", "Y=0")
  rownames(conf_table) <- c("phat=1", "phat=0")
  conf_table
}

Conclusion

From the descriptive statistics, It can be noticed that for the categories of technology (data channel is tech) and social media (data channel is socmed), the percentage of news articles that are popular is significantly higher than those that are not popular. On the other hand, for the categories of world (data channel is world) and entertainment (data channel is entertainment), the percentage of unpopular news articles is larger than the popular ones. This pattern suggests that the audience of Mashable.com has a stronger preference for news related to technology and social media, rather than world and entertainment news.

In the Regression Analysis, I evaluated the performance of random forest bagging and lm models, and compared them using the RMSPE metric to determine which model performed better. Before evaluating the data, I transformed the shares data by taking the logarithm.

Regarding the classification, I obtained an AUC score between 0.67 and 0.7, which is considered reasonably good. I conducted a confusion matrix on the random forest model and found that most of the observations were correctly predicted. Therefore, the machine learning model performed well.

Based on the analysis of the data, some actionable insights can be provided to content creators and marketers to improve the popularity of their articles:

The data suggests that articles related to technology and social media tend to be more popular than articles related to world and entertainment. Therefore, content creators and marketers should consider focusing on creating content related to technology and social media to increase the likelihood of their articles being popular.

The analysis also showed that articles with longer headlines tend to be more popular. Therefore, content creators should focus on creating compelling, longer headlines to attract readers and increase the chances of their articles being shared.

The analysis suggests that articles that contain images, videos, and other multimedia tend to be more popular than articles without them. Therefore, content creators should aim to include multimedia content in their articles to increase the chances of their articles being shared.

The analysis showed that articles with a positive sentiment tend to be more popular than those with a negative sentiment. Therefore, content creators should aim to create content that is positive and uplifting to increase the likelihood of their articles being shared.

Overall, these insights suggest that content creators and marketers should focus on creating content related to technology and social media, with longer headlines, multimedia content, and a positive sentiment to improve the popularity of their articles. By incorporating these strategies into their content creation, they can increase the likelihood of their articles being shared and ultimately improve their content strategies.
